e trade. This encourages offers that are attractive (weakly value-improving) to both potential recipients, or at least clearly positive to one with a chance the other might also accept. Over three short rounds, with each player proposing three times in a fixed order, we expect a small number of implemented trades, focused mainly on shifting BLUE toward cat and some modest inventory reshuffling between otter and peacock. Players’ moderate patience and mixed guardedness suggest that they will avoid obviously negative-surplus trades and converge quickly toward simple, one-color-for-one-color deals at coarse exchange rates (e.g., 1 RED for 2 BLUE, 1 RED for 3 BLUE), rather than complex multi-chip bundles.",
