{
  "game_explanation": "All three players start with symmetric endowments (10 RED, 10 BLUE, 10 GREEN) but asymmetric private values for RED and BLUE. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so incentives hinge on how much each player privately values RED and BLUE relative to that anchor and to one another.\n\nValuations:\n- Badger: RED=$0.80, BLUE=$0.80, GREEN=$0.50 (both colored chips are equally and strongly preferred to GREEN).\n- Camel: RED=$0.60, BLUE=$0.40, GREEN=$0.50 (RED>GREEN>BLUE, dislikes holding too many BLUE relative to the others).\n- Squid: RED=$0.20, BLUE=$0.60, GREEN=$0.50 (BLUE>GREEN>RED, strongly dislikes RED compared to others).\n\nTrue bilateral surplus opportunities are therefore:\n- Between Badger and Squid: Trade RED from Squid to Badger in exchange for BLUE from Badger to Squid is jointly efficient, because Badger values RED much more than Squid does, while Squid values BLUE almost as much as Badger. There is also some scope to move GREEN either way because both Badger and Squid prefer their high-valued color (RED or BLUE) to GREEN.\n- Between Badger and Camel: Badger likes BLUE more than Camel does, while both value RED above GREEN. This creates surplus from moving BLUE from Camel to Badger, potentially against GREEN or modest RED in return.\n- Between Camel and Squid: Camel dislikes BLUE, Squid dislikes RED. There is clear two-way surplus in swapping Camel’s BLUE for Squid’s RED. Both would also be willing to move some GREEN, but since they both strictly prefer GREEN to their least-valued color (BLUE for Camel, RED for Squid), GREEN mainly acts as a medium of exchange or filler if one side wants more volume.\n\nHowever, none of the players see others’ valuations; they only know the commonly stated value ranges and their own calculator, which shows them their personal gain or loss on any prospective trade. This pushes them toward strictly non-negative deals from their own perspective. Because acceptance is simultaneous and the recipient is randomized if more than one accepts, proposers face uncertainty not just about whether someone will accept but also which counterpart they will actually trade with. That uncertainty discourages finely targeted, one-sided proposals; instead it pushes toward offers that are at least weakly acceptable to more than one counterpart or clearly targeted to a single likely taker.\n\nGiven the personas:\n- Badger is moderately exploratory, with decent bookkeeping and mixed guardedness. He is likely to probe early with near-fair or slightly self-favoring terms, using the calculator actively but not pushing extremely aggressive ratios.\n- Camel has low acceptance thresholds and low exploitation caution. He will tend to accept any offer that gives him even a modest gain, and he is less likely to reject a mildly uneven split. As a proposer, he is numerate and can construct reasonable offers, but he is not strongly aggressive and may prioritize getting some deal done over perfect extraction.\n- Squid is very numerate and reflective, with low exchange aggressiveness but decent strategic patience. He will avoid losing trades and will only take neutral or better deals; however, he is not a holdout type who insists on very large margins. As a sender, he is likely to search a bit and fine-tune offers, but he may avoid highly exploitative rates.\n\nAcross the three rounds (nine total proposal turns), the likely pattern is an exploratory first round where each player discovers that the others will not accept strongly negative terms, then some convergence in later rounds towards simple, value-aligned trades (e.g., Camel and Squid swapping Camel’s BLUE for Squid’s RED, or Badger and Squid aligning high-value colors and shedding low-value ones). Because only one trade can occur per proposal and inventory constraints matter, even mutually beneficial directions may not be fully exploited; players may grab reasonably good, easy-to-see gains rather than engineer long, multi-step inventory reshuffles. Randomization when multiple accept will also encourage offers that are acceptable to whichever counterpart actually executes, not bespoke for only one.\n\nThe reconstructed game below follows this logic: early near-miss attempts, then a series of modest, individually profitable trades that fit each player’s values and personas, with Camel relatively quick to accept small gains, Squid careful but cooperative, and Badger probing then locking in safe improvements.",
