o accept any calculator-negative deal and doesn’t demand high margins; she will take simple, clearly beneficial proposals and may settle quickly.\n\nUncertainty arises from:\n- Private values: each player knows only their own red/blue valuations, so they must infer others’ preferences from trade attempts and responses.\n- Random partner selection when multiple accept: this can make players shade offers to be slightly attractive to both counterparts if they mainly care about getting a deal at all, not with whom.\n- Limited horizon (3 rounds): with only 9 total proposals, players cannot wait too long for a perfect deal. Especially Turtle (first mover every round) is likely to propose straightforward win–win trades early.\n\nMechanically, the surplus calculators strongly discipline behavior. Proposers will almost never send themselves into a clear negative-surplus trade; responders will nearly always accept when the calculator shows a non-trivial positive gain and reject when it shows a loss. That makes the game largely about discovering cross-value differences and splitting surplus with simple integer exchanges.\n\nGiven these elements, a likely observed trajectory is:\n- Early in Round 0, Turtle offers mild but safe terms (e.g., offering her somewhat-less-valued RED for GREEN or BLUE) that test others’ willingness to trade without being aggressive. Zebra tends to accept small, clearly good gains.\n- Gorilla follows with red-for-blue or red-for-green trades that give her more RED from Turtle or Zebra while paying with BLUE or GREEN. She is willing to give generous surplus to secure RED.\n- Zebra, when proposing, offers somewhat balanced blue/red for green or vice versa but doesn’t push others hard, and might occasionally see no obviously beneficial trade and simply make a conservative or exploratory offer that gets declined.\n\nAcross the three rounds, inventories gradually tilt toward each player’s preferred color (Turtle toward BLUE, Gorilla toward RED, Zebra toward