e rates and use them as a reference going forward, favoring fair, slightly win–win looking trades rather than extreme exploitation.\n\nUncertainty comes from: (1) who values which color most; (2) whether counterpart accept/reject behavior reflects strict valuation or broader fairness/strategy norms; and (3) the random tie-breaking when multiple players accept the same proposal. Because all proposals are public and responses are simultaneous, proposers must design offers that are net-positive for themselves based on their own calculator and still attractive enough that at least one counterpart will accept, while not being so attractive that both always accept when that randomness could shift gains toward the unintended partner. Over three rounds (nine total turns), they have limited time: players will likely move from exploratory trades in Round 0 toward more targeted, surplus-increasing trades in Rounds 1–2 once they infer that Kangaroo likely values RED/BLUE lower than Butterfly and Squid.\n\nGiven these incentives and personas, a plausible trajectory is: Round 0 contains probing offers around RED↔GREEN and BLUE↔GREEN from Butterfly and Squid, with Kangaroo experimenting but insisting on clear private surplus. Some early offers are declined when they clearly harm one side given the on-screen calculator. By Round 1, all three suspect that Kangaroo is a low-valuation holder of both RED and BLUE, so profitable patterns emerge: Kangaroo sells low-value BLUE (and sometimes RED) to Butterfly and Squid in exchange for GREEN; Butterfly and Squid sometimes contest the same attractive offers, leading to randomness in partner selection. Round 2 then refines these patterns, with remaining inventory constraints shaping who can still profitably trade which color. Overall, total surplus rises via moving RED and BLUE away from Kangaroo and, to a lesser degree, from Squid toward Butterfly when terms are mutually profitable.",
