uld also miscalibrate edge cases.\n\nBecause proposals are multilateral—any non-sender can accept—and ties are randomly resolved, players face the additional uncertainty of not controlling their trade partner when multiple others find a deal attractive. This randomness encourages more inclusive offers (profitable for the sender against either counterpart) or offers that are slightly better aligned with a targeted counterpart's likely values while still possibly attractive to the third player. The fixed proposer order (cat, iguana, zebra each round) and the short horizon (three rounds) mean that players cannot rely much on long-run reputation; instead, they focus on immediate, clearly positive trades as soon as good opportunities emerge. Early in the game, proposals act as signals of underlying values: for instance, iguana's strong bids for red and willingness to part with blue will reveal her preference ordering, while cat and zebra's trades that move blue toward themselves and red away from themselves signal their own rankings. By the final round, after some learning from observed history, we expect players to close remaining mutually beneficial gaps, especially by moving remaining red chips toward iguana and blue chips toward cat and zebra if inventory and prior trades allow.\n\nIn this forecast, the realized path emphasizes relatively simple, surplus-sharing trades that respect each player's likely caution level and numeracy. Cat tends to initiate conservative, near-fair terms that favor moving into blue; iguana focuses on accumulating red via blue and sometimes green; zebra accepts many small positive deals, often paying with red or green to grow her blue holdings. Not all proposals clear: some are declined when they offer minimal or no gain to the prospective recipient or when the terms are skewed enough to trigger rejection given the recipient's acceptance threshold. Over three rounds, we see gradual convergence toward a pattern where iguana ends up with comparatively more red and less blue, while cat and zebra improve their blue holdings relative to red, consistent with the underlying value structure and behavioral priors.",
