  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features privately valued red and blue chips plus a common-value green chip. All players start with 10 of each color, know that everyone values green at $0.50, but do not see the others’ red/blue values. Alligator values red the most ($0.60) and blue moderately ($0.50); Buffalo values red and green equally ($0.50) and blue weakly ($0.20); Rabbit values red very highly ($1.00) and blue moderately ($0.30). In terms of surplus potential, Buffalo has the lowest blue value and middling red; Rabbit has the highest red; Alligator is in between but still likes red more than blue. This creates strong gains-from-trade in moving blue chips away from Buffalo toward Alligator or Rabbit, and moving red chips toward Rabbit if others underestimate how much she values them. Because green is common value, trades involving green mostly help rebalance inventories rather than create large surplus differentials.\n\nStrategically, Alligator is numerate, patient, and relatively accepting of small but positive gains; he is likely to propose tidy, surplus-positive offers that give others something but keep a small edge. Buffalo is more prosocial, somewhat anchor-sensitive, and less aggressive; she is willing to accept fair or slightly costly terms for group harmony but is averse to feeling exploited and is likely to seek closure by accepting clearly beneficial offers. Rabbit is disciplined, exploratory, and easy to satisfy; she will search for trades that convert her low-value blue into high-value red, and with a low acceptance threshold she is willing to take most clearly positive deals.\n\nKey uncertainties arise because each player knows only their own valuations. Alligator likely infers that others might value red somewhat more than blue but not how extreme Rabbit’s red value is. Buffalo may underestimate how much Rabbit wants red, so she may offer red too cheaply at first or hesitate to sell too much. Rabbit, seeing her own strong red preference, infers there are gains from buying red, especially from Buffalo, but cannot tell how others value blue relative to red. The simultaneous-response rule plus random matching when multiple players accept discourages hyper-targeted bilateral deals and encourages making offers that are attractive to either counterpart. Over three rounds (nine total proposal turns), players are likely to begin with cautious, modestly favorable offers and then adjust toward more clearly beneficial, almost risk-free trades as they see what gets accepted. With everyone relatively patient and at least two players having low acceptance thresholds, multiple accepted trades are likely, especially ones that move blue from Buffalo to Alligator/Rabbit and red from Alligator/Buffalo to Rabbit when the exchange rates look mutually profitable given each player’s private calculator.",
